Representation.Text: Key to Sea Robins and Sculpins

Label.Description: English vocabulary (undefined expertise level of audience)
Deutsch (erforderliches Fachwissen unbekannt, wurde nicht definiert)

Representation.Text: Has five gill openings on each side
Has either one or no gill openings on each side
The body in cross section is more or less rounded
lower jaw projecting so far beyond upper that most teeth in lower jaw exposed when mouth closed
most teeth in lower jaw not exposed when mouth closed
both eyes on same side of head
one eye on each side of head
Body tapers to a whiplike tail ("Rattail")
Triangular tail, straight or convex edge
Numerous light-producing organs (photophores) along the ventral surface
No light-producing organs (photophores) long the ventral surface
Body long and slender; body's greatest height (not counting dorsal fin) less than or equal to 1/5 of total body length
Body shorter and stouter; body's greatest height (not counting dorsal fin) greater or equal to 1/4 to total body length
The belly in cross-section has a bottom edge that is sharp-edged
The belly in cross-section has a bottom edge that is more or less rounded
Four or more small fins between last dorsal fin and caudal fin and between anal fin and caudal fin
No small fins between last dorsal fin and caudal fin and between anal fin and caudal fin
Base of longest dorsal fin 1/7 or less of total body length
Base of longest dorsal fin 1/6 or more of total body length
The front half of the first dorsal fin is supported entirely by segmented, fairly soft bones (called rays)
The front half of the first dorsal fin is supported entirely by unsegmented, often very hard bones (called spines)
Base of anal fin long, more than 1/5 of total body length. Pectoral fins large, usually more than 1/5 of total body length
If two dorsal fins are present, base of anal fin usually less than 1/5 of total body length. Pectoral fins small, usually less than 1/5 total body length
